          <head>
            <title type="main">
              <hi rend="i">DANCES OF ALBION</hi>
            </title>
          </head>
          <p>Monday, 25 July 1983, saw the sixteenth performance—since the first on 27 November 1980—of
the ballet <hi rend="i">Dances of Albion: Dark Night Glad Day</hi> by the Royal Ballet at the Royal Opera
House, Covent Garden. The music is Benjamin Britten’s <hi rend="i">Sinfonia da Requiem</hi> (1940) and his
<hi rend="i">Serenade for tenor, horn and strings</hi> (1942). The <hi rend="i">Serenade</hi>, written
originally for soloists Peter Pears and Dennis Brain, includes six English poems the imagery of which provides
the basis for Glen Tetley’s choreography. The poems, linked by the theme of evening, are by an anonymous
fifteenth-century writer, Blake, Charles Cotton, Ben Jonson, Keats, and Tennyson.</p>
